Money Stuff =0A The way US federal law works is that there is are only a fe=
w federal judges =0Ain the Fort Worth Division of the US District Court for=
 the Nort =0A=0A=0A <> =0A =0A<https://sli.bloomberg.com/click=3Fs=3D825881=
&stpe=3Ddefault&li=3D12305120&m=3D21d6dea82d6b16615cf44233be620525&p=3D0114=
2025>=0A=0A=0A=0AESG=0A=0AThe way US federal law works is that there is are=
 only a few federal judges in =0AtheFort Worth Division <> of the US Distri=
ct Court for the Northern District of =0ATexas, and they are extremely cons=
ervative. [1]  <> The best-known is Judge =0AReed O=E2=80=99Connor <>, =E2=
=80=9Cwho critics say <> has been a subject of =E2=80=98forum shopping=E2=
=80=99 by =0Aconservative plaintiffs seeking a sympathetic court in challen=
ges to federal =0Apolicies.=E2=80=9D So if you have a novel, conservative l=
egal theory, what you do is =0Ayou file a lawsuit in the Fort Worth federal=
 courthouse, and then you probably =0Aget assigned to Judge O=E2=80=99Conno=
r, and he probably endorses your novel legal =0Atheory. Then maybe the othe=
r side appeals, to the US Court of Appeals for the =0AFifth Circuit and per=
haps eventually to the US Supreme Court, but these days =0Athose courts are=
 also quite receptive to novel, conservative legal theories, so =0Ayour cha=
