ere are =0Abrothers-in-law, each with its own special characteristics, but =
they all =0Atraditionally involve insider trading.=0A=0ABut what about sist=
ers-in-law=3F This one was new to me <>:=0A=0AThe Securities and Exchange C=
ommission [yesterday] charged Alfred V. Tobia, =0AJr., the former president=
 and chief investment officer (CIO) of one public =0Acompany and a member o=
f the board of another, and his sister-in-law, Elizabeth =0ALee, with insid=
er trading that resulted in more than $428,000 in illegal =0Aprofits. The d=
efendants have agreed to pay more than $1.36 million to settle =0Athe charg=
es.=0A=0AWhat is the role of the sister-in-law in insider trading=3F Well! =
=E2=80=9CSince =0Aapproximately 2013,=E2=80=9Dsays the SEC <>, =E2=80=9CLee=
=E2=80=99s primary means of support has been =0Athe income from the stocks =
she owns and the proceeds of stock sales,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cmost =0Aof =
Lee=E2=80=99s stock investments have been based on recommendations or other=
 =0Ainformation she obtained from Tobia.=E2=80=9D So he was more or less re=
sponsible for =0Aher finances, and you can see how he might have been tempt=
ed to give her some =0Ainsider tips. For one thing, it=E2=80=99s more effic=
ient to tip her off about a few =0Amergers than it is to constantly give he=
r well-researched legal stock advice. =0AFor example:=0A=0AOn August 12, 20=
21, at 8:42 a.m., Lee texted Tobia, =E2=80=9CCan u advise a stock that =0Ap=
ays a nice dividend=3F=E2=80=9D=0A=0ATobia responded by texting =E2=80=9CNo=
,=E2=80=9D and a few minutes later texted, =E2=80=9CI have =0Aanother name=
=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CWill call.=E2=80=9D=0A=0AAnd then he allegedly calle=
d her with a tip about a public company that his =0Aemployer waslooking to =
acquire <>, and she then bought the stock. She just =0Awanted a nice divide=
nd! But he was busy! He was working on a merger! He didn=E2=80=99t =0Ahave =
time to research dividend stocks for her. He had another idea.=0A=0A=0AVide=
o games=0A=0AIf you keep your money in a bank, the bank is heavily regulate=
d. The bank has =0Apretty strict obligations to keep track of your money an=
d not lose it, and to =0Ahave good information security so nobody can steal=
 it. The bank will probably =0Ause your money for its own investing purpose=
s, but those investments are =0Arequired to be prudent, and there are capit=
al and liquidity requirements to =0Aminimize the risk that the bank won=E2=
=80=99t be able to give you back your money when =0Ayou ask for it. And the=
re is deposit insurance, so if the bankdoes lose your =0Amoney you can get =
it back anyway.=0A=0AIf instead you put all of your money into the online c=
urrency of a video game =0A=E2=80=A6 I don=E2=80=99tthink that there are to=
o many federal rules regulating the video =0Agame=E2=80=99s information sec=
urity regimes, capital or liquidity buffers, etc.=3F I =0Aconfess I am not =
an expert here, and this is neither legal nor financial nor =0Agaming advic=
e, but it seems right. And so if your favorite video game lets you =0Adepos=
it real US dollars to buy in-game gold ducats and keep them in the Goblin =
=0ABank, and the company that makes that game takes all the ducats in the G=
oblin =0ABank (kidding: all the dollars it got for ducats) and loses them d=
ay-trading =0Asingle-day options (in real life), and then you try to spend =
your ducats in the =0Agame and/or withdraw them for dollars, and the compan=
y is like =E2=80=9Csorry bro, =0Aducats are gone,=E2=80=9D then =E2=80=A6 (=
1) that seems like a weird but somehow plausible =0Abusiness model for a vi=
deo game company these days, (2) probably financial =0Aregulators aren=E2=
=80=99t going to stop them before they do it and (3) probably the =0AFedera=
l Deposit Insurance Corp. isn=E2=80=99t going to bail you out after they do=
 it.=0A=0AThe natural conclusion from this, to me, is =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99=
t keep your money in the =0AGoblin Bank in a video game,=E2=80=9D which fra=
nkly strikes me as bulletproof, but I =0Asuppose I am out of touch with tod=
ay=E2=80=99s financial and gaming world. Another =0Apossibility is =E2=80=
=9Cwell of course US financial regulatorsshould supervise video =0Agames <>=
=E2=80=9D:=0A=0AThe federal consumer watchdog agency on Friday proposed a r=
ule to give virtual =0Avideo game currencies protections similar to those o=
f real-world bank accounts.=0A=0AThe move acknowledges the explosion in new=
 forms of in-game currency, in which =0Aplayers convert dollars to other un=
its that can be reverted back to money or =0Atraded with other users. The g=
overnment=E2=80=99s new interpretation would apply =0Afinancial protections=
 so players can receive refunds or compensation for =0Aunauthorized transac=
tions, similar to how banks are required to respond to =0Aclaims of fraudul=
ent activity.=0A=0AThe regulator involved here is the Consumer Financial Pr=
otection Bureau, so =0Athe proposals <> involve things like disputing fraud=
ulent transactions. Not =0Adeposit insurance, or capital requirements. Give=
 it time though. Also here is a =0ACFPB consultative document with the unfo=
rtunate title =E2=80=9CLFG (Looking for =0Agamers): CFPB wants to hear abou=
