"margin: 16px 0;">If you keep your money in a bank, the bank is heavily reg=
ulated. The bank has pretty strict obligations to keep track of your money =
and not lose it, and to have good information security so nobody can steal =
it. The bank will probably use your money for its own investing purposes, b=
ut those investments are required to be prudent, and there are capital and =
liquidity requirements to minimize the risk that the bank won=E2=80=99t be =
able to give you back your money when you ask for it. And there is deposit =
insurance, so if the bank=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0</em>lose your money you can g=
et it back anyway.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If instead you put all =
of your money into the online currency of a video game=C2=A0=E2=80=A6 I don=
=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>think=C2=A0</em>that there are too many federal rules r=
egulating the video game=E2=80=99s information security regimes, capital or=
 liquidity buffers, etc.=3F I confess I am not an expert here, and this is =
neither legal nor financial nor gaming advice, but it seems right. And so i=
f your favorite video game lets you deposit real US dollars to buy=C2=A0in-=
game gold ducats and keep them in the Goblin Bank, and the company that mak=
es that game takes all the ducats in the Goblin Bank (kidding: all the doll=
ars it=C2=A0got for ducats) and loses them day-trading single-day options (=
in real life), and then you try to spend your ducats in the game and/or wit=
hdraw them for dollars, and the company is like =E2=80=9Csorry bro, ducats =
are gone,=E2=80=9D then =E2=80=A6=C2=A0(1) that seems like a weird but some=
how plausible business model for a video game company these days, (2) proba=
bly financial regulators aren=E2=80=99t going to stop them before they do i=
t and (3) probably the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. isn=E2=80=99t going =
to bail you out after they do it.=C2=A0</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Th=
e natural conclusion from this, to me, is =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t keep your =
money in the Goblin Bank in a video game,=E2=80=9D which frankly strikes me=
